#
# Semgrep file-level suppressions for hypatia. Used in tandem with the
# inline `// nosemgrep:` directives that already document audit intent
# at the call-site level (see clients/rust/hypatia-client/src/ffi.rs).
#
# Why a file-level entry: cargo fmt periodically relocates inline
# trailing-comment `// nosemgrep:` directives off the `unsafe {` line
# they were guarding, and semgrep's GitHub Code Scanning integration
# does not honour the preceding-line directive style as a substitute.
# Maintaining the inline annotations is still worthwhile (they're the
# canonical record of which unsafe blocks have been audited and why),
# but the file-level entry below ensures the audit isn't repeatedly
# re-flagged after each cosmetic reformat.
#
# Scope of the entry: clients/rust/hypatia-client/src/ffi.rs is the
# Rust client's FFI bridge to the Hypatia C ABI (libhypatia.so). Every
# `unsafe` block in the file is paired with a `// Safety:` comment
# above it explaining the invariants the caller relies on (see the
# Idris2 ABI proofs and the Zig `export fn` declarations referenced
# in those comments for the formal side). Any other security concerns
# that turn up in this file should be reviewed on their own merits;
# this entry only silences the blanket `unsafe-usage` rule.

clients/rust/hypatia-client/src/ffi.rs
